Date: 17 Apr 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: Office International des Epizooties (OIE), Alert Message [edited]
<http://www.oie.int/Messages/030416BEL.htm>

Strong Suspicion of Avian Influenza in Belgium
----------------------
Translation of information received on 16 Apr 2003 from Dr Luc
Lengele, Chief Veterinary Officer, Animal Health and Animal Products
Department, Federal State Service for Public Health, Food Chain
Safety and Environment, Brussels:
Report date: 16 Apr 2003.
Nature of diagnosis: clinical and laboratory.
Date of initial detection of animal health incident: 15 Apr 2003.
Location: Meeuwen-Gruitrode district, Limbourg province.
Description of affected population: layers - breeding hens.
Total number of animals in the outbreak:
susceptible: 10 500
deaths: 550
destroyed: 9950
Diagnostic tests used: RT - PCR strain H7 N?.
Causal agent: avian influenza virus.
Source of agent / origin of infection: unknown.
Mode of spread: unknown.
Other epidemiological details: For 14 days, the farm is situated in a
preventive buffer zone.
Control measures:
- movement control inside the country;
- precautions at the border;
- stamping out;
- vaccination prohibited.
Animal Health Information Department
Office international des epizooties (OIE)
<information.dept@oie.int>
Further details will be published in the next issue of Weekly Disease
Information, available online as of Fri 18 Apr 2003 afternoon (GMT).
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
