Source: EUobserver.com, 17 Apr 2003 [edited]
http://www.euobserver.com/index.phtml?aid=10951

Bird flu outbreak in Belgium
----------------------------
A highly contagious poultry disease -- dubbed 'bird flu' -- has
spread to Belgium, prompting the Federal government and the European
Commission to swiftly act to contain it.
Since traces of the avian influenza were discovered in Limburg
province on 15 Apr 2003, the Belgian government has ordered the
slaughter of some 250 000 birds.
Fearing the economic damage that could be done to the poultry
industry, the European Commission has decided to "reinforce the
control measures" already put in place by the Belgian government. It
has asked that no poultry or hatching eggs be allowed to leave
Belgium to other EU member states or third countries.
According to La Libre Belgique, the large supermarkets in Belgium are
not yet too concerned. Louis-Philippe Ouwerx, spokesperson for
Carrefour Belgium, said "We are not concerned ... All the quality and
control measures have been taken."
Member state experts will get together to discuss the emergency
measures imposed on Belgium on 25 Apr 2003.
[Byline: Honor Mahony]
