[3]
Date: Thu, 17 Apr 2003
From: Chris Griot <Christian.Griot@ivi.admin.ch>
Source: Health - AFP via YahooNews, 16 Apr 2003 [edited]

Belgium bans poultry transport as bird flu suspected
-----------------------------------------------------
Belgium slapped a ban on transport of live poultry and eggs after the
discovery of a suspected case of bird flu, which is already
afflicting farms in the Netherlands. Authorities concluded that there
was a "serious suspicion" that the illness had spread into the
country, after the possible case was reported in northeastern Belgium
on Wednesday, near the Dutch border.
The federal food safety agency AFSCA, which revealed the suspect case
in the commune of Meeuwen-Gruitrode, announced a ban on the transport
of live birds and poultry, day-old chicks, and hatching eggs. The ban
also applies to the transport of eggs for consumption from poultry
farms -- although not those already in the distribution system -- as
well as of pigs, cattle, goats, horses, and manure from the same
farms. The Belgian farm where the suspect case was been found is
within a buffer zone set up on 4 Apr 2003 after cases were found a
few kilometers away in the south of the Netherlands.
Dutch authorities last month launched a mass cull of chickens after
the discovery of suspected cases of bird flu. Bird flu, also known as
avian influenza, is viral disease that is highly contagious to
chickens, turkeys, ducks, and other birds but not dangerous for
humans or other animals.
Belgian authorities have also ordered the slaughter of all poultry
within a 3-kilometer (2-mile) radius of the affected farm, which
houses some 10 500 hatching chickens. The European Commission has
been informed of the suspect case and the measures taken, AFSCA said.
The Dutch poultry sector is one of Europe's largest. In 2001 the
Netherlands exported 7.9 billion eggs with a total value of 427
million euros, while the export of poultry meat brought in almost one
billion euros.
In Hong Kong a bird flu outbreak in February [2003?] claimed the life
of one man but Dutch virologists say the Hong Kong case is a
different, more dangerous strain of the virus than that in the
Netherlands.
