[4]
Date: Thu, 17 Apr 2003
From: ProMED-mail <promed@promedmail.org>
Source: EU Press release IP/03/552, 16 APR 2003 [edited]
<http://europa.eu.int/rapid/start/cgi/guesten.ksh?p_action.gettxt=gt&doc=IP/03/552|0|RAPID&lg=EN&display=>

Avian Influenza in Belgium: Commission adopts control measures
--------------------------------------------------------------
Following a suspected outbreak of avian influenza Belgium on 15 Apr
2003, the Commission adopted a decision today to reinforce the
control measures already put in place by the Belgian authorities.
Avian influenza is a highly contagious poultry disease that can cause
severe economic damage to the poultry industry.
Suspicion of an outbreak of avian influenza in the province of
Limburg arose yesterday. The Belgian authorities, in cooperation with
the Commission services, immediately put in place measures foreseen
in Directive 92/40/EC. Additional more stringent measures have been
adopted by Belgium.
The Commission Decision adopted today reinforces these measures by
defining them at the EU level. The Commission Decision specifies that
no live poultry, hatching eggs or fresh, unprocessed poultry manure
or litter may be dispatched from Belgium to other Member States or
third countries. They may also not be transported within Belgium.
However, in view of the specificity of poultry production, the
Belgian veterinary authority may authorise certain movements of
hatching eggs, day-old chicks, ready-to-lay pullets, and poultry for
immediate slaughter within Belgium. Strict rules will also apply for
the collection, storage, and transport of table eggs. Bio-security
and hygiene measures, including cleaning and disinfection procedures
at all levels of poultry and egg production, should be reinforced by
Belgium to prevent the further spread of the disease.
The measures contained in the Commission Decision are applicable
until 25 Apr 2003 and will be reviewed at the meeting of the Standing
Committee on the Food Chain and Animal Health scheduled for 23 Apr
2003. The urgent measures adopted by the Commission could then be
updated to take into account the development of the situation.
The Commission will continue to work closely with the Belgian
authorities to ensure proper coordination within the EU.
--
ProMED-mail
<promed@promedmail.org>
[The Belgian Animal Health and Animal Products Department, Federal
State Service for Public Health, Food Chain Safety and Environment
(In French -- AFSCA, in Flemish --FAVV:
<http://www.favv.fgov.be/indexNL.htm>) has published 3 press
releases on the issue since 16 Apr 2003. According to those, a
seriously suspected case of avian influenza was reported in
Meeuwen-Gruitrode (province of Limburg) on Tue, 15 Apr 2003. The
initial laboratory results were received during the night 15/16 Apr
2003.
Subsequently, the ASSCA/FAVV decided to impose a standstill
throughout the entire country, coming into effect on Wed 16 Apr 2003,
12.00 noon. This includes also a ban on all movements of ungulates
from farms where poultry are kept as well. Table eggs are not allowed
to leave poultry farms.
The affected farm is situated within the buffer zone, adjacent to the
Dutch border, established on 4 Apr 2003. Initial investigations have
not revealed any previous contacts with the Netherlands. 8 poultry
farms within a radius of 3 km of the affected farm have already been
depopulated. - Mod.AS]
